<TEXT>
a black bear and a mule deer buck are 
the first large animals confirmed killed by the forest fires in and 
near yellowstone national park and firefighters have been warned 
to avoid any injured animals 
yellowstone national park officials had repeatedly said that 
larger animals such as deer elk bison and bear can easily 
sidestep fires that advance normally 
however fires in the yellowstone area have not behaved 
normally veteran firefighters in and around the park say they have 
never seen fire move so far so quickly 
the black bear was suffering from deep burns on its feet and was 
unable to do more than lift its head friday evening said tom 
safford a highway patrolman who was given permission by state and 
local officials to shoot and kill the suffering animal about a half 
mile east of silver gate 
all four pads were burned off the feet and down to the bone 
he must have run through a bunch of hot coals it looked to me like 
he would have been permanently immobile safford said 
the bear about 4 years old had been seen lying in a marsh 
about 200 yards above a highway for about 24 hours before it was 
killed 
larry folenius safety officer on the storm creek fire told 
firefighters at saturdays 6 am briefing that there had been 
sightings of some hurt bears and cautioned firefighters to be 
careful around them if they were spotted 
about seven miles west of where the bear was killed the charred 
carcass of a mature buck deer lay beside the road to daisy pass 
fire scoured the area wednesday another carcass was reported to be 
nearby but could not be located 
</TEXT>
