<TEXT>
the serbian communist party chiefs 
public defiance of the national leadership has thrown this balkan 
country of competing ethnic groups into its most explosive 
political crisis of the postwar era 
slobodan milosevic on tuesday rejected a call from the federal 
communist party presidium to put an end to nationalist rallies in 
the southern province of kosovo where minority slavs contend they 
are harrassed by ethnic albanians who form 90 percent of the 
provinces population 
on tuesday more than 100000 serbs and montenegrins who are 
slavs staged protest rallies demonstrators shouted give us 
arms and army to kosovo underscoring the serbian 
leaderships demand to send the army to kosovo to restore order 
kosovo is an autonomous region within the republic of serbia 
milosevic and other serbian leaders want to change the federal 
constitution so the republic can assert control over kosovo and the 
autonomous province of vojvodina 
under the 1974 constitution serbia cannot interfere in kosovos 
judiciary police or other institutions 
leaders of other republics oppose the idea newspaper editorials 
have said that the foundation of the yugoslav state is threatened 
commenting on the showdown the daily vjesnik of zagreb capital 
of croatia warned that an increasing number of yugoslavs were 
questioning the 1943 agreement that gave birth to communist 
yugoslavia the nation is made up of six republics each of which 
has its own constitution assembly and president 
we witness a sharpening of nationalism and chauvinism on the 
entire yugoslav territory the editorial said 
milosevics supporters planned weekend rallies in the city of 
jajce where the agreement was worked out but local officials 
rejected the plan the organizers then said they would hold a 
solidarity meeting there sept 17 
milosevic has lashed out at the national leadership by saying 
the serbs and montenegrins have shown patience for the 
inefficiency of this country and the incompetence of its 
representatives 
in tuesdays speech he asserted yugoslav leaders failed to 
bring peace to kosovo referring to slavs living there he said 
this summer their patience came to an end 
milosevic defended the fastspreading serbian discontent as 
justified expression of popular sentiment while opponents say it 
will result in anarchy 
within hours the yugoslav communist partys central committee 
scheduled a session for late september to take action on kosovo and 
milosevic who enjoys popular support in serbia and the belgrade 
press 
on friday the tanjug news agency said a police unit from 
another part of serbia would leave for kosovo to reinforce local 
police 
on thursday more than 10000 serbs and montenegrins assembled 
at the kosovo town of vucitrn to protest what they called 
aggressive assaults of albanian chauvinists and separatists 
the belgrade daily politika reported 
the rally followed an attack last week on the home of a serbian 
woman two ethnic albanians convicted of damaging the house were 
sentenced to 30 days in jail the ethnic albanian judge involved 
was dismissed and the terms were increased to 60 days 
demonstrators were heard singing a folk song that boldly 
compares milosevic to the late president josip broz tito the 
virtually uncontested leader of nonaligned yugoslavia for three 
decades 
most belgrade newspapers give a lopsided view of what is going 
on in kosovo scene of bloody rioting for greater autonomy in 1981 
they keep reiterating that more than 30000 serbs and 
montenegrins left the province in recent years because of arson and 
other attacks blamed on albanians 
ethnic albanians are rarely given a chance to respond in public 
to what appear to be grossly distorted accounts 
in the regimecontrolled press the slav exodus is entirely 
blamed on the albanians an estimated 500 of whom are in jail 
the tanjug news agency reported friday that authorities in 
duesseldorf west germany warned albanian families from towns in 
macedonia they would be turned down as political refugees because 
their true motives are purely economic 
conversely serbian media have had practically no reports that 
slavs have relocated for economic reasons from kosovo yugoslavias 
most underdeveloped region 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
correspondent ivan stefanovic has been covering 
yugoslavia for the associated press for 33 years 
</TEXT>
