iran and iraq remained deadlocked at unmediated 
peace talks and a recess appeared near after both sides publicly 
accused the other of blocking progress 
in a statement friday iraq said talks cannot go anywhere unless 
the disputed shattalarab waterway is cleared and iraq is allowed 
free navigation in it shattalarab is iraqs only outlet to the 
sea and forms the southern boundary of the two nations 
the statement was in response to comments thursday by irans 
foreign minister ali akbar velayati velayati told reporters that 
iran considered the two issues related to the waterway extraneous 
elements that should be raised later in the talks 
the iraqi statement dismissed irans position as fantasy and 
accused tehran of wasting time 
a unsponsored ceasefire took effect aug 20 clearing the 
way for talks on a lasting settlement of the nearly 8yearold 
persian gulf war 
facetoface meetings were held only on the first two days of 
negotiations and neither foreign minister has met un mediator 
jan eliasson since last saturday lowerlevel contacts have 
continued 
signs increased friday that talks would be suspended over the 
weekend before resuming in new york later this month 
diplomatic sources speaking on condition of anonymity said 
eliasson was expected to announce a recess and that the last few 
days were spent haggling over a resumption date 
among irans priorities at the talks are a withdrawal of troops 
to internationally recognized boundaries exchange of war prisoners 
and a un investigation to determine who started the war 
on the border question the countries are at odds over a 1975 
treaty setting the iraniraq boundary down the middle of the 
shattalarab 
iraq has renounced the pact and claimed the entire waterway but 
iran says it still considers the treaty valid 
the waterway has been blocked by sunken ships since the start of 
the persian gulf war in september 1980 
