years after an equally rude uprooting at the hands of hurricane 
betsy 
as he sat among 1200 other evacuees at belle chasse high school 
just south of new orleans on friday night the 69yearold encalade 
said living through storms is a way of life 
people live all their lives down here he said you hate 
to leave you go somewhere else and a tornado will take you or 
something else will 
its discouraging but what are you going to do he said 
if youre too old you cant go far 
florence was at hurricane strength friday when the evacuees left 
their lowlying homes but lost its punch as it brushed the coast 
and was downgraded to a tropical storm this morning 
thousands of residents of coastal areas in mississippi alabama 
and florida also took refuge in shelters and homes of relatives and 
friends on higher ground 
despite an almost casual acceptance of his situation encalade 
said previous storms have cost him dearly 
when camille in 1969 and betsy came over they cleaned us 
out i lost two houses he said 
now encalade lives in a trailer in buras on the tip of the 
mississippi delta 
weve got it anchored he said but if the storm passes 
over its going to take it anyway so you just lock it up and come 
up here and see what happens 
at the school cots were set up in the gym with large families 
