<TEXT>
postmaster general anthony frank wants to 
bring americas generations closer together and if that brings the 
post office a little extra business he wont mind 
plant a family tree is the name of franks plan in which 
millions of family history forms will be given out in hopes that 
youngsters will write to their grandparents seeking information to 
fill them out 
letters provide an important link between families 
grandparents often meet their grandchildren through an exchange of 
letters and photographs long before they see each other 
facetoface frank said 
but it isnt just a business proposition says frank he could 
generate more business by concentrating on big advertisers and 
catalog companies 
the postal service is part of the fabric of american life we 
do more than deliver the mail we deliver ideas and dreams and help 
preserve our heritage he says 
as part of the family tree program the postal service has 
printed millions of folders which discuss family histories on one 
side and contain a genealogical form on the back to fill in 
information on parents grandparents and greatgrandparents 
the forms will be available free in post offices by the first 
week in october 
to get things started frank invited 27 third graders from dale 
city va to his washington office on friday to hear about the 
project and mail letters to their grandparents letters likely to 
get special treatment since they were handed directly to the 
postmaster general 
its just finding out about a generation you dont have much 
contact with frank said of his hopes for the program its 
children asking tell me about yourself gramps tell me about my 
parents when they were my age 
what a compliment to be asked about yourself by 
grandchildren frank added in an interview 
many youngsters will probably telephone for information of 
course but frank noted nostalgically you dont tie ribbons 
around old phone calls in the attic 
in some countries generations live together and get to know 
each other but thats not often the way in america as a result 
children tend not to know their grandparents very well frank 
explained to the youngsters 
were running out of glue in this country people are no 
longer as family oriented people are no longer as community 
oriented this is a try to bring the family together frank 
said 
victor hurst of the 30million member american association of 
retired persons hailed the program as a way of increasing harmony 
among people from different generations 
you can be sure our grandmothers and grandfathers will be as 
excited as can be to help all the grandchildren around the nation 
fill in the blanks in their family trees hurst said 
frank noted that only after becoming an adult do many people 
realize what they missed if they were not close to grandparents 
and by that time it is often too late 
in addition to providing a form for starting a family tree the 
folder includes tips on pursuing a more detailed family background 
including suggested sources for genealogical information such as 
the census national archives and national genealogical society 
