a japanese official said saturday he hopes 
president reagan will veto a bill approved by the us senate to 
curb textile imports to the united states 
it is regrettable that the us senate approved the bill 
ignoring the fact that us textile exports have increased and the 
industry did not perform as badly as many people believed said 
chang changhan acting secretary general of the taiwan textile 
federation 
the senate by a 5732 vote friday approved new curbs on 
textile clothing and shoe imports the bill still needs approval 
by the house of representatives before it can be sent to president 
ronald reagan 
the bill would freeze this years imports of textiles apparel 
and nonrubber footwear at 1987 levels and limit their growth to 1 
percent annually thereafter 
we hope president reagan will veto the bill if it is passed by 
the house chang said such a protectionist measure will only 
hurt american consumers who would have to pay higher prices for 
textile products 
the united states has been taiwans largest market for textile 
goods last year taiwans apparel and textile exports to the 
united states totaled 32 billion up 14 percent from 1986 
during a meeting in tokyo saturday with visiting us commerce 
secretary c william verity the japanese minister of international 
trade and industry hajime tamura expressed hope that the bill 
would be vetoed by reagan because of its protectionist nature 
a ministry official said 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
japanese government had issued no formal reaction to the bill 
however 
in hong kong a leading trade official said the bill was 
unnecessary and unlikely to survive a presidential veto 
the bill is totally unnecessary and inappropriate because 
the us textile industry has been doing well said miranda chiu 
acting assistant director of trade for the exportfueled british 
colony 
any protectionist measure would definitely have adverse 
effects on exporting countries such as hong kong chiu said 
she said it would be difficult to gauge the precise impact on the 
colony because the bill does not provide details on how it would be 
implemented 
exports from hong kong of apparel and clothing accessories to 
the united states reached 34 billion in 1986 up 9 percent from 
the previous year according to the census and statistics 
department 
exports of textile fabrics to the united states totaled 116 
million in 1986 up 11 percent from 1985 it said 
