<TEXT>
biba abdous children all skin and bones 
were smiling from eartoear as they played beside the familys 
10foodhigh millet crop the best they had ever seen 
my boys are skinny now but soon they will be fat said mrs 
biba whose family farms near karma about 35 miles northwest of 
nigers capital niamey we have never seen rain like this we 
are very content 
for the moment a droughtweary people have reason to smile 
all across west africas sahel abundant rains promise the best 
harvest in two decades 
nothing comes easy in the sahel a huge belt of land on the 
southern fringe of the sahara and the good rains are no exception 
more than 100 lives were lost in torrential rains thousands of 
homes destroyed and some farmland flooded an infestation of 
locusts also threatens some crops although the most immediate 
threat appears to be to the east in sudan 
the niger river rose to levels higher than any recorded in 
august since recordkeeping began in 1928 
scientists at a niamey agricultural weather center set up to 
monitor conditions in nine sahel nations after the disastrous 
197273 drought report the plentiful rain promises good harvests 
good pasturage is available for cattle goats sheep 
the sahel region is generally defined as covering the land south 
of the sahara with annual rainfall averaging from six to 24 inches 
it stretches from mauritania mali and niger in the north into 
northern nigeria and northern cameroon in the south 
many sahel regions had already received more than 14 inches the 
amount needed for millet crops by the end of august more 
important the rain had continued to fall since the beginning of 
june the crop needs rainfall throughout its threemonth growth for 
the best harvests 
the sahel nations burkina faso cape verde senegal niger 
mauritania mali chad guinea bissau and gambia have suffered 
recurring drought or generally inadequate rainfall since 1972 the 
nine nations cover more than 2 million square miles and have a 
population of about 40 million 
amadou djibo who farms with his father and three brothers about 
60 miles northwest of niamey said people werent concerned about 
losing their homes or flooding that had temporarily cut off an 
important road like the marabou storks who circled overhead the 
rains were considered a harbinger of better days 
we can always rebuild a house but if we have no rain we have 
no food he said 
djibo added that his village of zarakoire had not had an 
adequate harvest in seven years and life was hard 
boukar elhadj ousmane nigers minister in charge of animal and 
water resources said the rains had left 13 people dead and 7000 
homeless he also reported 15000 animals including goats sheep 
and cattle lost and about 600 miles of roads left temporarily 
impassable 
heavy rainfall has been reported across west africa extending 
into sudan in east africa where torrential rains and flooding 
resulted in 96 deaths and 200 million in damage 
in the sahel chad reported 45 people dead and 48000 homeless 
and 3500 cattle lost more than 50 people were killed in northern 
nigeria and thousands left homeless two dams burst after the 
heaviest rainfalls in 50 years cameroon and burkina faso also 
reported several deaths and many houses destroyed 
much flood damage was reported near rivers where people had 
moved in close to the water during drought years to plant gardens 
boukar said he could understand the attitude of peasants who 
minimized the importance of the damage and said we can consider 
the rain a blessing 
he added it gives them hope for the future many of those 
people have never seen this kind of rain in their lives they have 
only heard stories about it 
george eaton nigers director of the us agency for 
international development aid which was still distributing food 
donated to meet shortfalls from the last harvest said nigers food 
situation should be good after this harvest 
thats if the locusts dont eat it all or if there is so much 
there is still enough for the people eaton said he had received 
reports of good harvest prospects from aid directors in other sahel 
nations 
this has been a great morale booster even with the locust 
threat he added people are upbeat 
some harvesting already has begun in southern sahel regions 
where crops mature earlier but in most areas millet sorghum and 
other crops will be harvested in the coming weeks 
no one predicts an end to food shortages though given the 
probable reduction in us food aid because of the us drought the 
sahel rains were timely each sahel country has its own troubles 
and the rain certainly would create some problems even if it 
alleviated others 
and no one predicts that the drought cycle had been broken by 
the rains indeed scientists here would make no predictions at 
all noting a meterological institute had predicted three months 
ago that the sahel would experience a very dry year this year 
aid workers expressed concern the good rains will encourage 
pastoralists to rebuild their herds cut by as much as 50 percent 
by the massive 1984 drought to sizes the land cant support 
overgrazing has been a key factor in desertification the process 
by which the sahara claims land 
a pastoralists herd remains his bank and chief wealth in the 
sahel and governments have had little success dissuading their 
herdsmen from overgrazing the fragile land 
