<TEXT>
puerto ricans vote for a governor 
legislators mayors and a nonvoting member of the us congress on 
the same day mainland americans pick a new president but an 
underlining issue here is the seemingly neverending debate over 
the islands 36yearold commonwealth relationship with the united 
states 
puerto ricos three main political parties distinguished from 
each other primarily by their support for commonwealth statehood 
or independence all are seeking changes in what some of them see 
as the islands semicolonial status 
the outcome of elections here nov 8 is likely to hinge more on 
personalities and issues such as unemployment than on puerto ricos 
political status analysts say 
but both incumbent governor rafael hernandez colon the 
commonwealth candidate and his statehood rival mayor baltasar 
corrada del rio of san juan have pledged to hold a status 
referendum after the election 
the issue has featured prominently in the campaign so far 
it would be the first such referendum since 1967 when 60 
percent of the voters favored a continuation of the commonwealth 
arrangement 39 percent statehood and 1 percent independence 
puerto rico an island of 33 million mostly spanishspeaking 
people 1000 miles southeast of miami has flown the us flag 
since 1898 when spain ceded it to the united states at the end of 
the spanishamerican war 
the modernday commonwealth arrangement which went into effect 
in july 1952 gives puerto rico roughly as much control over its 
own affairs as any of the 50 states 
puerto ricans are us citizens but they pay no us taxes and 
cannot vote for president nevertheless they are eligible for us 
military service and social security and welfare benefits 
puerto rico receives substantial us aid 65 billion this 
year alone and us companies taking advantage of tax 
exemptions have given the island one of the strongest economies in 
latin america 
in return the united states uses puerto rico as a strategic 
base for naval operations and an important market for us goods 
the reality of the relationship as it is now 
procommonwealth commentator alex w maldonado wrote in the 
englishlanguage san juan star is enormously beneficial to 
puerto rico despite monumental efforts of president reagan and 
congress to cut domestic spending to reduce the gigantic federal 
deficit the flow of funds to the island has continued to grow 
yet there is dissatisfaction on all sides commonwealth 
supporters want more say in running the island statehooders 
complain of being treated as secondclass citizens and the 
independence movement fervently at times violently seeks 
undiluted puerto rican sovereignty 
hernandez colon 51 who is seeking his third fouryear term 
favors continued commonwealth status but wants washington to 
relinquish control over immigration foreign trade and certain 
environmental and labor matters 
his popular democratic party has announced plans for a 
referendum sometime after the election seeking maximum autonomy 
for puerto rico but the party has not specified what the term 
means 
corrada del rios new progressive party which wants puerto rico 
to become the 51st us state says its referendum would ask voters 
whether puerto rico should begin negotiations with the united 
states on statehood if approved the referendum would be followed 
by a second vote on any negotiated formula 
the tiny independence party which hasnt won more than 6 
percent of the vote in 20 years proposes an election of a 
multiparty assembly to resolve the sovereignty question and 
negotiate a solution with washington 
regardless of the outcome the election is unlikely to resolve 
the status issue the statehood party has twice held the governors 
office since it was founded in 1967 but has made no effort to 
achieve statehood while in power 
hernandez colon who has stressed his administrations economic 
record rather than the status issue is favored to win but it 
could be close 
an opinion poll of 600 registered voters carried out for san 
juans channel 2 television station in july put the incumbent 
governor 5 points ahead of corrada del rio 45 percent to 40 
percent with 4 percent backing the independence partys ruben 
berrios and the rest undecided the poll had a margin of error of 
plus or minus 43 percent 
</TEXT>
