<TEXT>
fiveyearold sergio neal was lucky to 
survive a fire that destroyed the small apartment where he lived 
with his mother and two sisters 
and he was fortunate to receive prompt expert care to treat 
second and thirddegree burns over most of his face his hands and 
chest and part of his arms and head 
but sergio featured recently in a newsweek article looking at 
the tragic ramifications of living in poverty is still very much 
in need 
his face was pitifully disfigured by the flames and he has not 
regained full movement of his hands 
he and his 2yearold sister shakeriay who was not as 
seriously injured spent a month at a shriners burn institute in 
cincinnati ohio after the december incident in this rural orlando 
suburb just a few miles down the road from walt disney world 
the newsweek story last month prompted offers of assistance from 
around the country some for medical care and reconstructive 
surgery a volunteer organization in apopka has set up a 
fundraising account for the neals 
a 6yearold girl from new jersey sent newsweek a letter 
containing two 1 bills and two nickels with a note saying would 
you please give this to sergio 
the fire started after the childrens mother audrey neal 
stepped out briefly to a neighboring apartment leaving sergio and 
shakeriay in the living room one of them evidently played with a 
cigarette lighter and fire quickly engulfed the small apartment 
wouldbe rescuers found one of the doors to the apartment 
boarded up they could not get the knob on the other door to work 
hearing the childrens screams and frantic fruitless efforts to 
open the front door ms neal and neighbors finally broke through 
the door fought the flames and carried the children out just as 
firefighters arrived rescue workers administered emergency medical 
treatment and rushed them to an orlando hospital 
a day after the blaze sergio and his sister were flown in 
separate learjet ambulances complete with a doctor nurse and 
medical technician in each plane from orlando to the shrine 
facility in cincinnati 
after their months stay sergio has continued to get outpatient 
care two or three times a month all of this expensive 
sophisticated treatment has been provided free by the shriners 
under their generous programs for needy burned and crippled 
children around the country 
still until sergio gets older there is little doctors can do 
about his scarred and pitted face 
much of the reconstructive surgery has to wait until bone 
growth stops probably around the age of 16 says victor clark 
childrens director of the bahia shrine temple in orlando who 
arranged for the neals treatment transportation and continuing 
visits to the cincinnati facility 
but were prepared to help him as long as he needs it up to 
the age of 21 says clark 
while sergios continuing medical treatment for his physical 
injuries is ensured there is some worry about his other 
notsoobvious problems and needs the mental anguish which is 
difficult to determine in a young child his education and the 
home care necessary before plastic surgery 
he now wears a plastic face mask which clark says puts pressure 
on facial scar tissue to make it grow sideways to decrease its 
thickness 
because of his facial disfigurement his mother is keeping him 
out of school and hopes to get him on a program that provides a 
visiting teacher for homebound students 
so while other kids his age are starting school sergio is 
spending hours in front of a tv or playing and squabbling with his 
two sisters and four cousins in the twobedroom apartment where 
they now live 
sergios mother and her three children moved in with her sister 
shawana and her four kids after the fire 
the basic problem is that they are so poor they have no 
resources for anything says social activist cathy moore about 
the neal family 
for one thing here are seven children and two adults living 
in a tiny apartment and now the landlord has given them an 
eviction notice 
ms moore director of a volunteer organization known as smile 
for single mothers in a learning experience said audrey neals 
family would like to move out but cant afford to do so 
sergios mother gets less than 350 a month in afdc the 
states aid to families with dependent children ms moore said 
whereas shed need an annual income of 15000 to qualify under a 
federally subsidized lowincome housing program 
ms moore set up the fundraising account for the neals to help 
them with housing and home health care and education for sergio 
meanwhile winter park attorney russell troutman one of the 
founders of a legalaid office for the poor in the apopka area 
said he was looking into the possibility of a liability lawsuit 
over the allegedly defective doorknob in the neal apartment 
as i understand it the kiddies were trying their best to open 
the door during the fire but the doorknob wouldnt work he said 
were looking into it 
the sergio neal case is just one example of how people tend to 
overlook those in need until disaster strikes ms moore said 
adding that articles like the one in newsweek just scratch the 
surface of the problem 
i hope we realize poverty is all around us she said that 
its not always something hidden behind the scenes 
</TEXT>
