<TEXT>
investors may be dissatisfied with the progress 
of stock prices lately but they should be pleased with rising 
dividends 
thats the case being argued these days by analysts who argue 
that the boring stock market of 1988 has actually produced more 
generous rewards than its notices would suggest 
when standard amp poors corp estimated recently that 
corporations might increase their dividends by as much as 10 
percent this year little loud cheering was heard on wall street 
dividends provide half the total return earned by common 
stocks historically yet wall street traditionally ignores them 
observed paul kuper executive vice president at the centre square 
investment group in philadelphia 
but watch out wall street dividends and more particularly 
dividend growth are likely to take a front seat with investors as 
the 5 to 6percent growth rate of the last five years doubles to 
10 to 12percent over the next few years 
it isnt hard to figure out why dividends didnt command as much 
attention as capital gains when the typical investor thought about 
the stock market in recent years 
if you tried to talk about dividends in the heady 198287 bull 
market you most likely would have been laughed out of the room 
and in the subsequent crash last fall the furthest thing from 
anybodys mind was a quarterly dividend check 
in any financial season most professional money managers and 
brokers arent paid by their clients to generate dividends 
however analysts who have delved into the subject say that to 
dismiss dividends as irrelevant misses the point 
we have always considered yield to be a bedrock indicator of 
value asserts john connolly at dean witter reynolds inc 
it is a hard number unlike earnings or book value which may 
exist only in the mind of an accountant 
declaring a dividend involves a cash payment it is not a 
decision that is taken lightly 
the dividend bulls base their optimism on several factors 
starting with the strong trend in corporate earnings that helps 
give boards of directors the option of voting dividend increases 
furthermore says kuper at centre square companies recently 
have been paying out less than 40 percent of their earnings as 
dividends which is close to a historic low a normal rate he 
says is more like 50 percent 
the tax reform act of 1986 he adds provided a spur to 
dividends since it eliminated the special tax treatment of 
longterm capital gains that means that dividends now have an 
equal value with capital gains for taxpaying investors 
based on his estimates for 1989 connolly figures the aggregate 
yield on the standard amp poors composite index of 500 stocks 
projects to 41 percent 
contrast that with the mere 26 percent available at the 
market top last year he says 
these numbers are unlikely to make anyones adrenaline flow 
he acknowledges stocks are bought for appreciation not yield 
but we are more interested in value than pizzazz at this 
stage and 41 percent is a comfortable number 
for the first twothirds of 1988 connolly adds the sampp 500 was 
up about 7 percent since the yield is about 4 percent total 
return is 11 percent 
this compares well with the 10 percent annual longterm 
return on stocks boring might not be so bad 
</TEXT>
